{{Infobox film | name = The Street | image = | image_size = | border = | alt = | caption = | director = [[Caroline Leaf]] | producer = [[Guy Glover]]<ref name=wise>{{cite book|editor=[[Wyndham Wise]]|title=Take One's Essential Guide to Canadian Film|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m4Y_OgckDmIC&pg=PA201&dq=The+Street+Leaf+Richler&hl=en&sa=X&ei=P5qrUKmsOvPK0AGvh4CwDA&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=The%20Street%20Leaf%20Richler&f=false|date=2001-09-08|publisher=[[University of Toronto Press]]|isbn=978-0802083982|pages=201–202|chapter=The Street}}</ref> | writer = | screenplay = | story = | based on = {{based on|[[The Street (story collection)|The Street]]|[[Mordecai Richler]]}} | narrator = | starring = [[Mort Ransen]] (voice)<ref name="NFB">{{cite web|url=http://www.onf-nfb.gc.ca/eng/collection/film/?id=10524|title=The Street|work=1976|publisher=National Film Board of Canada Web site|accessdate=2009-08-30}}</ref> | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = [[National Film Board of Canada]] | distributor = National Film Board of Canada | released = <!-- {{Film date|Year|Month|Day|Location}} --> | runtime = 10 m 12 s<ref name=wise/> | country = Canada | language = English | budget = | gross = }} '''''The Street''''' is a 1976 [[animated short]] by [[Caroline Leaf]], based on a [[short story]] of the [[The Street (story collection)|same name]] by [[Mordecai Richler]], and produced by the [[National Film Board of Canada]].
Animated using [[paint on glass animation]], and set on [[Saint Urbain Street]] in [[Montreal]], it explores the reactions of Jewish family in the early 20th century to the death of a grandmother.<ref name="CFE">{{cite encyclopedia|title=The Street|encyclopedia=Canadian Film Encyclopedia|publisher=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|url=http://tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/films/street|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824174926/http://tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/films/street|archivedate=2013-08-24|df=}}</ref>
==Awards== ''The Street'' garnered numerous awards including a special prize from the [[Melbourne International Film Festival]] and two [[Canadian Film Awards]] (now known as the Genie Awards) for Best Animated Film and the Wendy Michener Award, presented in recognition of outstanding artistic achievement in Canadian cinema.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Townend|first=Paul|title=Wendy Michener Award|encyclopedia=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica-Dominion]]|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/wendy-michener-award}}</ref> It was also nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]] at the [[49th Academy Awards]].<ref name="CFE"/>
